{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Albrecht_Dürer_-_Adam_and_Eve_(Prado)_2.jpg | title= Adam and Eve | artist= [[Albrecht Dürer]] | year= 1507 | medium= Oil on panel | dimensions= Two panels, each {{convert|209|x|81|cm|in|abbr=on}} | museum= [[Museo del Prado]], Madrid }}
'''''Adam and Eve''''' is a pair of [[panel painting|oil-on-panel]] paintings by German Renaissance artist [[Albrecht Dürer]].
Completed in 1507, the work followed a [[commons:File:Adam Eva, Durer, 1504.jpg|1504 copper engraving]] by Dürer on the same subject, one which offered Dürer the opportunity to depict the ideal human figure. Painted in Nuremberg soon after his return from Venice, the panels were influenced by Italian art. Dürer's observations on his second trip to Italy provided him with new approaches to portraying the human form. Here, he depicts [[Adam and Eve]] at human scale—the first full-scale nude subjects in German painting<!--source: Russian, Spanish wikis-->.
''Adam and Eve''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s first home was the [[Prague Castle]], the property of collector [[Rudolf II]]. During the [[Thirty Years' War]], armies plundered the castle and the panels came to be owned by [[Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden]]. His daughter, [[Christina of Sweden|Christina]], gave the work to [[Philip IV of Spain]] in 1654. Later King [[Charles III of Spain|Charles III]] ordered in 1777 that the painting be hidden in the [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]]. It arrived at its current home, Madrid's [[Museo del Prado]], in 1827, but was not publicly displayed until 1833.<!--provenance source: Spanish wiki-->
