'''Ahn Sahng-hong'''{{efn|{{korean|hangul=안상홍}} can variously be seen [[Korean romanization|represented in Latin letters]] as Ahn Sahng Hong, Ahn Sahng-hong, Ahn Sahnghong, Ahnsahnghong, Ahn Sang Hong, Ahn Sang-hong, Ahn Sanghong, Ahnsanghong, An Sahng Hong, An Sahng-hong, An Sahnghong, Ansahnghong, An Sang Hong, An Sang-hong, An Sanghong, and Ansanghong. [[Korean name]]s follow the ''<[[family name]]> <[[given name]]>'' pattern, but his name is sometimes romanizised using the Western pattern ''<given name> <family name>'', consequently e.g. Sang Hong Ahn, Sang Hong An etc. can also occur.}} ({{korean|hangul=[[wikt:안|안]] [[wikt:상|상]] [[wikt:홍|홍]] | hanja=[[wikt:安|安]] [[wikt:商|商]] [[wikt:洪|洪]] | rr=An Sanghong}}; 13 January 1918&nbsp;– 25 February 1985) was a [[Korea]]n [[Christian]] [[Religious minister|minister]] and founder of Witnesses of Jesus Church of God.{{efn|{{Lang-ko|하나님의교회 예수증인회|links=no}}. Translation in a more direct word order would be "Church of God Witnesses of Jesus".}}{{r|doctrinemanual}}{{rp|7–8}}{{r|inch106doctrines}}

Shortly after his death in 1985 a [[Schism (religion)|schism]] took place dividing Witnesses of Jesus Church of God into two [[sect]]s, [[:ko:새언약 유월절 하나님의교회|New Covenant Passover Church of God]]{{efn|{{Lang-ko|새언약 유월절 하나님의교회|links=no}}}} and what is today known as [[World Mission Society Church of God]].{{efn|{{Lang-ko|하나님의교회 세계복음선교협회|links=no}}. Translation in a more direct word order would be "Church of God World Mission Society". This word order has previously been used by the organization.{{r|wawocogwms}} 복음 can also translate to "gospel",{{r|dicgospel}} and the full name can e.g. be seen translated to "Church of God World Gospel Association."{{r|kcourt2005}}}}{{r|inch106doctrines}} Both organizations claim him as their founder; New Covenant Passover Church of God regard Ahn as a teacher,{{r|ncpcoghistory}} World Mission Society Church of God regard Ahn as [[God]].{{r|wmscogabraham}}

== Biography ==

=== Early life ===
Ahn was born to [[Korean Buddhism|Buddhist]] parents{{efn|By 1918 Buddhism was the predominant religion in Korea. By 2010, according to a survey cited by ''[[The World Factbook]]'', 2013–14 edition, Christians accounted for 31.6% (Protestant 24%, Roman Catholic 7.6%) and Buddhists for 24.2% of the South Korean population.{{r|CIA}}}} on 13 January 1918 in the small, [[rural]] village of Myeongdeok-[[Ri (administrative division)|ri]] in the [[North Jeolla Province]] at a time when [[Korea under Japanese rule|Korea was under Japanese rule]]. The family [[Human migration|migrated]] to [[Busan]], where Ahn grew up in the [[Haeundae District]], the city in which he would later found his church.{{r|issues141144}}{{rp|127}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{rp|339}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{rp|65}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|489}}{{r|nrk2002}}

=== Conversion to Christianity ===
From 1937, during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] and [[World War II]], Ahn and his mother lived in [[Japan]] over a nine-year period. He returned to Korea in 1946, after the war, and began attending the local congregation of the [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]] in [[Incheon]] in 1947.{{r|issues141144}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{r|nrk2002}} Ahn reported getting [[revelation]]s in 1953,{{r|CarfS}} and [[Renunciation|renounced]] his Buddhist faith and was [[Believer's baptism|credobaptised]] on 1948{{r|ikccah2012}}{{efn|Previously a baptismal date of 16 December 1948 performed by a [[Pastor]] Lee Myeong-deok in Incheon has been reported, but the source for this date and name is obscure, and no written record exists.{{r|issues141144}}{{rp|125}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{rp|338}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|494}}{{r|issue348}} The published references writes that with a 1948 baptism the ministry of Ahn was {{Circa}} 37 years (1948–1985),{{r|issues141144}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{rp|75}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{r|history1999}} which has been used in argument for him fulfilling a [[Davidic dynasty in Bible prophecy|Davidic]] prophecy being the [[Second Coming]] of Jesus, the use of the honorific ''Christ Ansanghong'', and the assertion that he [[Entering heaven alive|ascended]] rather than died by the World Mission Society Church of God.{{r|david}} The investigation by The International Korean Christian Coalition against Heresy of the protocol from the Seventh-day Adventist Church stating Ahn was baptised on 9 October 1954 by a Pastor Gim Seo-gyeong showed, that while Pastor Gim could be confirmed, no Pastor Lee Myeong-deok was with the church in 1948.{{r|ikccah2012}}}} In 1956 Ahn proclaimed that "Within 10 years there will be a [[Second Coming]] of [[Jesus]]."{{r|issues141144}}{{rp|127}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{rp|339}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|489}}{{r|2007cults}}{{rp|90}}{{r|amen12676-1948-88a}} On 5 April 1958 he married Hwang Wonsun (1923–2008),{{efn|{{lang-ko|[[wikt:황|황]] [[wikt:원|원]] [[wikt:순|순]] | links=no}}; {{transl|ko|''hwang-won-sun''}}{{r|BjS4Y}}}} with the marriage producing three children.{{r|interview with ahn kwang-sup}}{{r|grave2}}

=== Own church ===
Ahn grew critical to [[Seventh-day Adventist theology|teachings]] in the [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]], and the church [[Excommunication|excommunicated]] him in March 1962 over disputes about the [[Christian cross|cross]] as a [[religious symbol]].{{r|inch106doctrines}}{{r|issues141144}}{{rp|128}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{rp|65}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|490}}{{r|nrk2002}}{{r|ikccah2012}}{{r|elijahand}}{{rp|30}} Twenty-three people followed Ahn and left the church, and two years later on 28 April 1964, Ahn established his church '''Witnesses of Jesus Church of God'''{{efn|{{Lang-ko|하나님의교회 예수증인회|links=no}}. The name "Church of God", mentioned several times in e.g. [[Paul the Apostle]]'s [[First Epistle to the Corinthians|First]] and [[Second Epistle to the Corinthians]], and in his [[Epistle to the Galatians]],{{r|01GQg}} is a name used by numerous, mostly unrelated [[Christian denomination]]al bodies.{{r|Melton2005}} Ahn in ''Doctrine Manual of the Witnesses of Jesus Church of God'' (1972) cites [[First Epistle to the Corinthians]] and [[First Epistle to Timothy]]{{r|jpZC1}} as the source for "Church of God", and several [[Chapters and verses of the Bible|verses]] in [[Acts of the Apostles]] as the source for "Witnesses of Jesus".{{r|doctrinemanual}}{{rp|7–8}}}} in [[Busan]].{{r|inch106doctrines}}{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{r|nrk2002}}{{r|金洪喆1989}} Witnesses of Jesus Church of God expanded to 13 congregations in [[South Korea]] before Ahn's death in 1985.{{r|issue348}}{{r|mr141-144}}{{r|ZTrAB}}

=== Beliefs ===
Major [[dogma]]ta are outlined in ''Doctrine Manual of the Witnesses of Jesus Church of God'' (1972),{{r|doctrinemanual}} and detailed in the more than two [[dozen]] books Ahn wrote. His original publications as well as scans of his notes and extant [[sermon]]s have been made available online.{{r|ashpubs}} Ahn argued that the practice of the [[Apostolic Age|apostolic early church]] had been distorted and his [[Restorationism|restorational]] doctrines and practices included:{{r|inch106doctrines}}
# Women should wear [[Christian headcovering|headcovering]] while praying.
# [[Baptism]] is the first step towards [[Salvation (Christianity)|salvation]].
# The [[Sabbath in Christianity|Sabbath]] should be kept on [[Sabbath in seventh-day churches|Saturdays]], not Sundays.
# [[Christmas]] should not be celebrated as Jesus' birthday because it is the anniversary of the [[Solar deity|sun god]].
# The [[Christian cross|cross]] is considered a form of [[idolatry]].
# The [[Passover (Christian holiday)|Passover]] and Festival of Unleavened Bread should be kept.
# Keeping the feasts in [[Book of Leviticus]] {{bibleref2|LEV|23|NIV|chapter 23}}: [[First Fruits]], [[Festival of Weeks]], [[Feast of Trumpets]], [[Day of Atonement]]; and [[Feast of Tabernacles]].

==== Eschatology ====
Ahn, who like most Christians{{r|EricksonHustad2001}} believed in the [[Second Coming]] of Jesus,{{r|doctrinemanual-secondcoming}} had predicted a Second Coming "within 10 years" in 1956.{{r|issues141144}}{{rp|127}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{rp|339}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|489}}{{r|2007cults}}{{rp|90}}{{r|amen12676-1948-88a}} In the tradition of [[Seventh-day Adventist eschatology]], which had been suppressed by [[Kuniaki Koiso]] during his wartime rule of Korea,{{r|Kang1997}} Ahn further believed to be living in the [[end time]] and that the Second Coming was imminent. As Korean [[Protestant]]s earlier in the 20th century had perceived [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese occupation]] by identifying symbolically with the history of Israel,{{r|ParkPak2011}} Ahn through biblical [[exegesis]] in his book ''The Mystery of God and the Spring of the Water of Life'' (1980){{r|The Mystery of God and the Spring of the Water of Life}} interprets the [[Gospel of Matthew]] {{bibleref2|MT|24|NIV|chapter 24 verse 32-34}} to suggest that the world could come to an end in 1988, 40 years after the [[Israeli Declaration of Independence|independence]] of the modern state of [[Israel]].{{r|amen12676-1948-88a}} Ahn's original ''The Mystery of God and the Spring of the Water of Life'' is made available [http://www.ncpcog.co.kr/rb/home/c/21/22/57 online]; World Mission Society Church of God in their later editions of the book have deleted information pertaining to the failed prediction.{{r|amen12676-1948-88a}} Ahn in his book ''The Bridegroom Was a Long Time in Coming, and They All Became Drowsy and Fell Asleep'' (1980){{r|The Bridegroom Was a Long Time in Coming, and They All Became Drowsy and Fell Asleep}} in a discussion based on [[Typology (theology)|scriptural typology]], presented his conclusion that the world would come to an end in 2012:
{{Quote box
| title = 
| quote = Since the day that the [[Ten Commandments]] was received, it took 168 days to build the [[tabernacle]] and to hold the ceremony, and as the fulfillment of this prophecy, Jesus also went into the heavenly Most Holy on the 10th day of the 7th month in 1844 which is the [[Day of Atonement]], and since then began to build the heavenly temple for 168 days namely 168 days until the ceremony. The [[prophecy]] is to be interpreted as 1 day to 1 year ([[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]] {{bibleref2|Ezekiel|4:6|NIV|4:6}}; [[Book of Numbers|Numbers]] {{bibleref2|NUM|14:34|NIV|14:34}}. Therefore, adding 168 years to 1844 when Jesus entered the heavenly Most Holy, [[2012 phenomenon|2012 becomes the last day]].
| align = center |width = 60% |border = |fontsize = |bgcolor = |style = |title_bg = |title_fnt = |tstyle = |qalign = |qstyle = |quoted = 
{{hidden end}}
| salign = right
| source = <small>Ahn Sahng-hong, ''The Bridegroom Was a Long Time in Coming, and They All Became Drowsy and Fell Asleep'', 1980 & 1985</small>{{r|The Bridegroom Was a Long Time in Coming, and They All Became Drowsy and Fell Asleep}}
