=== Death ===
Following a [[heart attack]] during lunch on 24 February 1985, Ahn had a [[stroke]] en route to hospital, and died the next day, 25 February 1985 in the Catholic [[Maryknoll]] Hospital{{efn|{{lang-ko|메리놀병원|links=no}}; Also romanizised ''Merinol Hospital'' after its pronunciation, {{transl|ko|''me-ri-nol-byeong-won''}}{{r|KfqTp}}}}{{r|PnYUn}} in [[Jung District, Busan]].{{r|doctorsnews}} Ahn Sahng-hong was 67 years old. He was survived by his wife and three children.{{r|inch106doctrines}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{rp|337}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{rp|65}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|494}}{{r|nrk2002}}

Ahn was [[Burial|buried]] in a public [https://maps.google.com.au/maps?hl=en&q=%EC%84%9D%EA%B3%84%EA%B3%B5%EC%9B%90&ie=UTF-8 grave] located in Seokgye [[Cemetery]]{{efn|{{lang-ko|석계공원묘지|links=no}}; {{transl|ko|''seok-kkye-gong-won-myo-ji''}}{{r|9dsHw}}}}{{r|ikccah1572grave}} {{convert|30|km}} north of Busan. From the time of his burial in 1985, a single [[tombstone]] stood beside the grave, the [[epitaph]] reading: "The grave of the prophet [[Elijah]] Ahn Sahng-hong."{{efn|{{lang-ko|선지 엘리야 안상홍 지 묘|links=no}}}}{{r|grave}}{{r|grave85ex}} After the death of his wife Hwang Won-sun 23 years later on 4 September 2008, she was buried in the plot beside Ahn, and a new tombstone carrying both their names (as well as their children's on the back) replaced the 1985 stone, repeating the epitaph.{{r|grave2}}{{r|ikccah2023grave}}

== Legacy ==
The unexpected death of Ahn gave rise to a power struggle within Witnesses of Jesus Church of God:{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|ncpcog-after-death}} some people in the church wanted to continue along the lines laid out by Ahn, others wanted to re-introduce the concept of a "spiritual mother" embodied in the then 41-year-old woman named [[Zahng Gil-jah]]{{efn|{{lang-ko|장길자|links=no}}; {{transl|ko|''jang-gil-ja''}}{{r|5CDJm}}}} (born 1943).{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|nrk2002}}{{r|interview with ahn kwang-sup}}{{r|ikccah2023grave}} After an [[extraordinary general meeting]] in Witnesses of Jesus Church of God on 4 March 1985 failed to reconcile the opposing factions, a [[Schism (religion)|schism]] divided the church into two [[sect]]s{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|inch106doctrines}}{{r|nrk2002}}
;* New Covenant Passover Church of God,{{efn|{{Lang-ko|새언약 유월절 하나님의교회|links=no}}}} and
;* Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong Church of God.{{efn|{{Lang-ko|하나님의교회 안상홍 증인회|links=no}}. The name is reflected in the domain name WATV.ORG registered in February 2000{{r|whoiswatv}} the [[acronym]] standing for '''W'''itnesses of '''A'''hnsahnghong '''T'''ele'''v'''ision.{{r|watvname}} {{Lang-ko|하나님의교회 안상홍 증인회|links=no}} can be seen in other translations, e.g. a more direct word order "Church of God, Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong", or "Church of God, Association of Ahnsahnghong's Witnesses".}}

=== New Covenant Passover Church of God ===
One group of people in Witnesses of Jesus Church of God stayed on the premises in Busan. Among them were Ahn's wife and their three children. This sect is today known as New Covenant Passover Church of God. Ahn's son Ahn Kwang-sup{{efn|{{lang-ko|안광섭|links=no}}; {{transl|ko|''an-gwang-seop''}}{{r|etrmd}}}} (born 1954) is an elder in the church and continues to expound on his father's work.{{r|oqm59}} An outside observer visited the church and had this comment:
{{Quote box
| title = |quote = The service performed at the New Covenant Church is not much different from that of the [[Mainstream Christianity|mainstream churches]]. The parishioners pray in the name of '[[Jesus]] Christ' and recite the [[Lord's Prayer]]. They sing unmodified mainstream [[hymn]]s. Like the Seventh-day Adventists, they observe Saturday as the [[Sabbath in seventh-day churches|Sabbath day]].|align = center |width = 60% |border = |fontsize = |bgcolor = |style = |title_bg = |title_fnt = |tstyle = |qalign = |qstyle = |quoted = 
{{hidden end}}
| salign = right
| source = <small>Lee Seung-yeon, in ''Modern Religion'', February 2012</small>{{r|interview with ahn kwang-sup}}
}}

=== Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong Church of God ===
Another group of people in Witnesses of Jesus Church of God including the man Kim Joo-cheol{{efn|{{lang-ko|김주철|links=no}}; {{transl|ko|''gim-ju-cheol''}}{{r|mP8a9}}}} and the woman [[Zahng Gil-jah]] wanted to re-introduce the concept of a "spiritual mother", and on 22 March 1985 moved from Busan to [[Seoul]].{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|inch106doctrines}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{r|nrk2002}} On a meeting in Seoul on 2 June 1985, they established a church called Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong Church of God. Two major new doctrines were codified{{r|amen12676-1948-88a}}{{r|ikccah2023}}
;*Ahn Sahng-hong should be regarded as Jesus Christ who had already come, should be titled ''Christ Ahn Sahng-hong'', and pursuant to a traditional [[Trinity|trinitarian]] view of Christian [[Hypostasis (philosophy and religion)|hypostasis]] Ahn was consequently also [[Holy Spirit|The Holy Spirit]], [[God the Father]], and thus [[God]].{{r|PXIZX}}
;*Zahng Gil-jah should be regarded as [[Heavenly Mother|God the Mother]], a female image of God,{{r|God Elohim}} be titled ''Heavenly Mother'', or simply ''Mother'', and together with Ahn Sahng-hong be regarded as God.{{r|God Elohim}}
A change in religious practice, as reflected in the change of name from "Witnesses of Jesus" to "Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong", was, that prayers were no longer conducted in the name of [[Jesus Christ]] but in the name of ''Christ Ahn Sahng-hong''.{{r|inch106doctrines}}

The [[Apotheosis|deification]] of Ahn Sahng-hong and Zahng Gil-jah has been "harshly criticized,"{{r|kcourt2005}} and has led to the church being officially [[Damnation|condemned]] by The National Council of Churches in Korea as an [[interdenominational]]ly combatted, [[Blasphemy|blasphemous]], [[Heresy|heretical]] [[cult]].{{r|kncc}}{{r|KOR43208.E}}

As a central argument to the claim that Ahn Sahng-hong should be the Second Coming of Jesus, and in turn an argument for his suggested promotion of Zahng Gil-jah to the Bride of the Lamb, is the proposition that he fulfilled a [[Davidic dynasty in Bible prophecy|Davidic]] prophecy by preaching 37 years from his baptism 16 December 1948 to his death on 25 February 1985,{{r|david}}{{r|952summarize}} a period which in reality was only 36 years, 2 months, and 9 days.{{r|36years}} The source for the baptismal date of 16 December 1948 performed by a [[Pastor]] Lee Myeong-deok in Incheon is however obscure, and no written record exists.{{r|issues141144}}{{rp|125}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{rp|338}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|494}}{{r|issue348}} In 2011 a protocol from the Seventh-day Adventist Church was discovered, stating Ahn was baptised when he was 36 years old on 9 October 1954 by a Pastor Gim Seo-gyeong. The investigation by The International Korean Christian Coalition against Heresy showed, that while Pastor Gim could be confirmed, no Pastor Lee Myeong-deok was with the church in 1948, reducing the length of the ministry of Ahn from 36 years to 30 years and 4 months.{{r|ikccah2012}}
;1988 failed doomsday prophecy
Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong Church of God announced that "1988 is the end of the world" citing [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] {{bibleref2|MT|24|NIV|24:32-34}} as Ahn had done in his 1980 book ''The Mystery of God and the Spring of the Water of Life''.{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|The Mystery of God and the Spring of the Water of Life}}{{r|wa1988end1}}{{r|wa1988end2}} A few thousand members of Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong Church of God gathered on a mountain in [[:ko:소정면|Sojeong-myeon]], [[Yeongi County]], [[South Chungcheong Province]] awaiting the coming of Christ Ahn Sahng-hong, preparing for the [[rapture]] and the [[Salvation (Christianity)|salvation]] of [[144000 (number)|144,000]] souls. When Ahn [[Unfulfilled Christian religious predictions|failed to appear and nothing happened]] the church updated their apocalyptic forecast and scheduled it to the opening of the 1988 Olympics in Seoul later that year where the members gathered and preached the end of the world would come by the end of 1988 and that Ahn Sahng Hong would come again. WMSCOG later claimed it was a fulfillment of the preaching of Johna.{{r|inch106doctrines}}{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|emerging1992}}{{rp|342}}{{r|heresy1999}}{{rp|77}}{{r|heresy2000}}{{rp|494}}{{r|nrk2002}}{{r|issues88-90}}{{r|renamed-cwm}}

Around 1997, Witnesses of Ahn Sahng-hong Church of God had established a non-profit organization titled the Church of God World Mission Society for the purpose of registering and managing the organization's assets.{{r|kcourt2005}}{{r|renamed-cwm}}

