{{Eastern Christianity}}
'''Catholicosate''' or '''catholicate''' designates a particular ecclesiastical primacy, headed by a primate titled as [[Catholicos]]. Such regional primacies exist within various branches of [[Eastern Christianity]], especially those of [[Oriental Orthodox]] tradition. The term ''catholicosate'' also designates the area of responsibility (territorial or otherwise) of a [[catholicos]]. The word is derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] Καθολικος, meaning "wholeness" and it was used to designate ecclesiastical primacy of some major metropolitan sees.
While a catholicos is sometimes considered to correspond to a [[bishop]] in the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] and [[Protestantism|Protestant]] traditions, a catholicate is typically a larger and more significant organizational division than a [[Diocese|bishopric]], [[archdiocese]] or [[episcopal see]]. Catholicates often have distinct cultural traditions established over many centuries.
Within the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] there are two catholicosates: the [[Mother See of Holy Etchmiadzin]] in [[Etchmiadzin Cathedral|Etchmiadzin]], [[Armenia]], and the [[Holy See of Cilicia|Catholicosate of the Great House of Cilicia]] in [[Antelias]], [[Lebanon]]. In the 10th century, when lands inhabited by Armenians were devastated by [[Seljuks]], the Armenian church took refuge in [[Cilicia]]. In the 15th century, a new catholicos was elected in Etchmiadzin.<ref>[http://www.westernprelacy.org/pages/arm-church.htm History of The Armenian Church] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20040812224331/http://www.westernprelacy.org/pages/arm-church.htm |date=2004-08-12 }}</ref>
While some traditions favor the [[English language]] spelling "catholicate", others favor "catholicosate." There is a degree of inconsistency in this regard. Others spellings, including "catholicossate", are seen as well.
